Participants were first vaccinated with influenza, and inoculated with 
 S. pneumoniae 3 days later. 117 participants completed the primary study end points and 114 returned their symptom log questionnaires for data analysis (LAIV n = 53, TIV n = 61). As previously described, demographics were similar in both groups 
 [18]. 47 participants (41%) became experimentally colonised; 45.3% (n = 24) and 37.7% (n = 23) in the LAIV and TIV groups, respectively. Overall 34.0% (18/53) participants in the LAIV group and 49.2% (30/61) participants in the TIV group reported one or more nasal or non-nasal symptoms, or both, at any time point in the 9 days following vaccination. Statistical difference between these two groups was seen for most nasal symptoms with less symptoms reported in the LAIV group (
 Fig. 1; 
 Fig. 2 right panel; 
 Suppl Table 2).
